    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="background">

Here&apos;s something that, if true, would offer an answer to the question
BAILAR has been posing, concerning the point of STS.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="26" relname="span"> If someone can
actually confirm what SCHMAUS is saying below,</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="19" relname="span"> then that would indeed be
an example of the kind of thing I&apos;m endorsing as good STS practice. </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="20" relname="span">

However, until shown otherwise, I remain skeptical of the existence of a
Kantian philosophical lobby that goes around hounding the American Medical
Association.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="24" relname="span">  What strikes me as more likely is that there were already
some social movements interested in promoting the autonomy of patients </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="elaboration">
and the Kantian rhetoric had an edifying quality that was likely to prove 
persuasive in public settings.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="21" relname="span"> The use of philosophy as a resource for 
legitimating social projects is not new,</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="elaboration"> and it&apos;s not even bad.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="22" relname="span"> But it&apos;s not 
quite the same as the philosopher herself being &apos;proactive&apos;.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="9" relname="concession"> But I&apos;m 
prepared to be proven wrong on this point. </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="12" relname="preparation">

On Thu, 27 Oct 1994 STXSCHMAUS@minna.acc.iit.edu wrote</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="27" relname="span">

For example, I may be wrong about this, but it was not doctors
&amp;gt; who came to philosophers asking them how they could act less paternalistic-
&amp;gt; ally.  I think it was philosophers who were bringing traditional, perhaps
&amp;gt; Kantian, concerns about the moral autonomy of human  beings to bear on 
&amp;gt; a &quot;practical&quot; question.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="31" relname="span">

Finally, I am genuinely baffled by the following remark, </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="29" relname="span">since for -- 
better or worse</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="14" relname="concession"> (and it may be the latter) --</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="30" relname="span"> I make a point of 
practicing what I preach.</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="32" relname="span"> What it may mean is that I have a bad theory of 
rhetoric!</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="17" relname="background">

&amp;gt; 
&amp;gt; In your book, Steve, you argue theoretically against giving rhetoric a
&amp;gt; bad name.  But you continue to use it on the list in a way that 
&amp;gt; contributes to its bad reputation!
&amp;gt;</segment>
